### The pre-authorised code

GOV.UK Wallet uses the [pre-authorised code flow](https://openid.net/specs/openid-4-verifiable-credential-issuance-1_0.html#section-3.5) for credential issuance. This flow works as follows:

* your credential issuer authenticates the user with GOV.UK One Login
* your credential issuer generates a pre-authorised code to start the credential issuance process - this code acts as proof that the user has already been authenticated
* your credential issuer passes this pre-authorised code to GOV.UK Wallet
* GOV.UK Wallet uses this pre-authorised code to request an access token and a refresh token (if [in-app refresh](refresh-credentials/in-app-refresh) is implemented) from GOV.UK One Login
* GOV.UK Wallet uses the access token from GOV.UK One Login to retrieve the credential
* When the issued credential expires, GOV.UK Wallet uses the refresh token to request a new access token and then retrieve a new credential

 The pre-authorised code flow makes getting credentials simpler by letting your credential issuer start the authorisation flow. In a standard authorisation flow, GOV.UK Wallet would need to start the flow. In the pre-authorised code flow, the credential issuer starts the authorisation flow and passes the details to GOV.UK Wallet (via the pre-authorised code) so that GOV.UK Wallet can continue.

The pre-authorised code is a JWT generated and signed by your credential issuer and included in the credential offer.

#### JWT Header

The JWT header must contain the following parameters:

```JSON
{
  "kid": "5dcbee863b5d7cc30c9ba1f7393dacc6c16610782e4b6a191f94a7e8b1e1510f",
  "typ": "JWT",
  "alg": "ES256"
}
```

| Parameter                                                                          | Description                                                                                                                                                                    |
|------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
|`kid`      | Must match a `kid` in the JSON Web Key Set (JWKS) published to your [`/.well-known/jwks.json`](/issue-a-credential/jwks) endpoint.     |
|`typ`      | This is the media type of the complete JWT. It must be set to `JWT`.      |
|`alg`      | This is the algorithm used to sign the JWT. It must be set to `ES256`.    |

#### JWT Payload

The JWT payload must contain the following claims:

```JSON
{
  "clientId": "<YOUR ONE LOGIN CLIENT ID>",
  "credential_identifiers": [
    "<CREDENTIAL IDENTIFIER>"
  ],
  "credential_configuration_ids": [
    "fishingLicence"
  ],
  "exp": 1234567890,
  "iat": 1234567890,
  "iss": "https://example-credential-issuer.gov.uk",
  "aud": "https://token.account.gov.uk"
}
```

| Claim                                                                          | Description                                                                                                                                                                    |
|------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| `clientId`      | Your client ID, which you received when you registered your service to use GOV.UK One Login.   |
| `credential_identifiers`     | The unique identifier for the specific credential offer. GOV.UK Wallet currently only supports one identifier per pre-authorised code. This should be a long random value (for example, a UUIDv4) and should not be a personal identifier or account identifier.     |
| `credential_configuration_ids`     | The unique name of the credential. The value used here must match the name of the credential used in the `credential_configurations_supported` parameter of your [credential issuer metadata](../metadata/#response-format).     |
| `exp`         | The expiration date of the pre-authorised code. We recommend this is aligned with the length of time a user can remain inactive on your service, up to a maximum of 1 hour. Must be expressed in epoch time, in seconds, as per the [IETF RFC 7519](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc7519).     |
| `iat`         | The time at which the pre-authorised code was issued. Must be expressed in epoch time, in seconds, as per the [IETF RFC 7519](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc7519).     |
| `iss`         | The URL of your credential issuer.      |
| `aud`         | The URL of the authorisation server your credential issuer relies on for authorisation. This must be set to the GOV.UK One Login authorisation server: `https://token.account.gov.uk/`.     |

#### Signature

You must sign the pre-authorised code with an Elliptic Curve Digital Signature Algorithm (ECDSA) private key for signing. You must make the corresponding public key, which forms a pair with the private key used for signing, publicly accessible at your [`/.well-known/jwks.json`](/issue-a-credential/jwks) endpoint. This is because GOV.UK One Login will need access to the public key to verify the signature on the pre-authorised code.

The signing algorithm must be ECDSA with the P-256 curve and the SHA-256 hash function.

### Storing the credential information

You need to store some context to track the credential issuance process.

You must store the:

- credential offer identifier: this is the `credential_identifiers` in the pre-authorised code payload described above
- GOV.UK Wallet subject identifier (`walletSubjectId`): this was included in the user information your service received when the user authenticated with GOV.UK One Login
- credential details: this could be an identifier for the record to be issued as a credential and/or other relevant information about the credential itself

You could also choose to store the:

- offer creation timestamp: this records when the credential offer was created
- offer expiration time: this indicates when the credential offer will expire

Storing this information allows your credential issuer to track which credential is being offered and to which recipient and GOV.UK Wallet instance, and the specific context of the issuance request.

There is a [reference implementation of the credential issuer](https://github.com/govuk-one-login/mobile-wallet-example-credential-issuer) which uses AWS DynamoDB as the storage solution.

### The credential offer URL

Your credential issuer must pass the credential offer to GOV.UK Wallet by value with a URL.

The URL for passing a credential offer by value is in the following format:

1. The GOV.UK Wallet credential offer endpoint
2. A query parameter `credential_offer` that contains the Base64Url-encoded credential offer object

